# 1. Open 'Keychain Access' on your Mac.
# 2. In the menu bar, choose Keychain Access → Certificate Assistant → Request a Certificate From a Certificate Authority...
# 3. Enter your Apple ID email.
# 4. Leave Common Name and CA Email Address empty.
# 5. Choose Saved to disk.
# 6. Save the certificate signing request file, usually a .certSigningRequest.
# 7. Go to Apple Developer Portal (https://developer.apple.com/account/resources/certificates/add) and create a new certificate:
# 8. Under "Software", choose "Developer ID Application" and continue.
# 9. Upload the .certSigningRequest file you saved earlier and download the generated certificate.
# 10. Double-click the downloaded certificate to add it to your Keychain.
# 11. In Keychain Access, find the certificate you just added (it should be named something like "Developer ID Application: Your Name (TEAMID)").
# 12. For APPLE_SIGNING_ID, use the identity name portion, for example: "Your Name (TEAMID)".
# 13. The build script also accepts the full Keychain label and strips the "Developer ID Application:" prefix automatically.
APPLE_SIGNING_ID=""

# Your Apple Account email used for notarization submissions.
# Get this from the Apple ID account that has access to your Apple Developer team.
APPLE_ID=""

# Your Apple Developer Team ID.
# Get this from Apple Developer -> Membership details, or from the team shown in
# Certificates, Identifiers & Profiles.
APPLE_TEAM_ID=""

# An app-specific password created for the Apple ID above.
# Create it at appleid.apple.com -> Sign-In and Security -> App-Specific Passwords.
APPLE_APP_SPECIFIC_PASSWORD=""

# Optional local path used only for the real-app integration test fixture.
# Point this at a local Gitvan SQLite database only if you intentionally run that test.
GITVAN_REAL_DATABASE_PATH="/absolute/path/to/gitvan.sqlite"